properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are occurring. Visibilities have been slowly improving, however, visibilities are still near 800 m with winds of 50 gusting to 60 km/h. Winds are expected to quickly weaken early this evening improving visibilities significantly. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A prolonged period of very cold wind chills is expected. Temperatures near -40 and moderate northwesterly winds are expected to give wind chill values near -55 tonight and tomorrow morning. As the wind weakens tomorrow afternoon, the wind chill is expected to moderate. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Freezing Rain Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing rain is expected to develop this evening from Red Deer to Drumheller, and then spread eastwards through Hanna and Coronation overnight. After the freezing rain, 5-10 cm of snow is expected to fall on top of the ice covered surfaces. ### Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Freezing rain warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ABstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ABStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills is expected. A cold airmass remains entrenched over the central Arctic. Air temperatures approaching -40C combined with wind speeds up to 20 km/h is expected to produce extreme wind chill values of -55 this evening. Conditions may improve overnight with increased cloud cover. ### Extreme cold puts everyone at risk. Watch for cold related symptoms: shortness of breath, chest pain, muscle pain and weakness, numbness and colour change in fingers and toes. Extreme cold warnings are issued when very cold temperatures or wind chill creates an elevated risk to health such as frost bite and hypothermia. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. Snow has already began in Churchill. This afternoon heavier snow will move into the area accumulating 10 cm tonight with a total of 15 cm by Wednesday morning. Northerly winds are expected to increase to 40 gusting to 60 km/h overnight and into Wednesday morning bringing blowing snow with reduced visibilities. Snow is moving into the area from northern Alberta ahead of a low pressure system that has so far accumulated 17 cm in Fort Smith. ### Rapidly accumulating snow could make travel difficult over some locations. Snowfall warnings are issued when significant snowfall is expected. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
